******
[2] South Carolina
Date: Thu 4 Sep 2014
Source: Colleton Today [edited]
http://www.colletontoday.com/news/horse-dies-of-sleeping-sickness-in-colleton-news-the-press/article_e152f14a-3399-11e4-8927-001a4bcf887a.html


Late last week [week of 25 Aug 2014], the South Carolina Veterinarian's Office verified that a horse in Colleton County had been stricken with eastern equine encephalitis (EEE), 1 of 7 cases of the almost always fatal disease in the state so far this year [2014].

Dr Adam Eichelberger, director of Animal Health Programs at Clemson University, said officials who monitor the disease only identify the county where an EEE case is reported to protect the privacy of the owner of the stricken horse. Officials of the South Carolina Department of Health and Environmental Control [DHEC], he added, work with the state veterinarian's office to handle the individual cases. DHEC also conducts spraying in the areas where the horse had been stricken to control the mosquito population. Eichelberger said weather plays an important role in the number of EEE and West Nile cases his office will handle in the course of a year. "2003 had been the 1st time we had had significant numbers of EEE." Then there was 2013, when 49 horses in South Carolina were stricken with EEE. "We were the number one state in the country." 48 of those horses died from the disease. Colleton County had one reported EEE case in 2013.

Eichelberger points out that in the years leading up to 2013, the number of horses contracting EEE was very low. He suggests that was a contributing factor to the high number of cases in 2013. "As soon as you stop having any cases, people start forgetting about it, " he suggested. The number of cases soared in 2013 because "when we did have an ideal environment for mosquitoes, some people quit obtaining vaccinations." He also suggests because the state was experiencing a poor economy, some horse owners decided to forego the expense of the vaccinations.

Eichelberger suggests that there are a number of reasons for the decrease. South Carolina had a colder winter and a drier spring and summer than last year [2013]. He also believes that increased awareness of EEE and West Nile virus has people "doing a better job of spraying and getting vaccinations. West Nile virus and EEE are very similar," he said. Both affect the central nervous system and in both cases the vectors are mosquitoes. EEE is the more deadly to horses. 9 out of 10 horses will die from EEE. Around 4 out of 10 will die from West Nile. "We have known about EEE for years; West Nile is a newer disease."

"Vaccines are very effective for both diseases," Eichelberger said. "With vaccinations and good mosquito management you can eliminate the issue. "You typically see EEE and West Nile in the summer and early fall," he said. "Last year [2013], our 1st case was in June, this year the 1st case in August."

[byline: George Salsberry]

